175
00:26:52,680 --> 00:26:53,715
How's school?

176
00:26:56,200 --> 00:26:58,475
Mmm. I'm on what they call
a pre-business track.

177
00:26:58,640 --> 00:27:01,552
Just junk, mostly, buying and
selling, like Mrs. Chambers.

178
00:27:02,440 --> 00:27:06,228
Mama wanted me to be a teacher,
but I said forget that no-money crap.

179
00:27:06,400 --> 00:27:10,109
A blue volvo and job security
will make me a happy camper.

180
00:27:11,480 --> 00:27:13,710
My worst nightmare is
I turn into another Ricky.

181
00:27:16,560 --> 00:27:19,677
Oh, well.  Tchk.
As one of my professors says,

182
00:27:19,920 --> 00:27:22,718
"Necessity has always been
our easiest excuse."

183
00:27:24,760 --> 00:27:28,548
What would you teach?
I mean, children.

184
00:27:30,080 --> 00:27:31,638
How to survive.

185
00:27:34,160 --> 00:27:35,832
With your soul intact.

186
00:27:37,840 --> 00:27:40,673
Yeah. I guess that's it.

187
00:27:53,480 --> 00:27:55,516
<font color="#ffff00">Today, lunch with Rochelle.</font>

188
00:28:04,560 --> 00:28:06,437
<font color="#ffff00">I don't know what I'm doing here.</font>

189
00:31:21,040 --> 00:31:22,712
<font color="#ffff00">Call it an experiment.</font>

190
00:31:23,200 --> 00:31:26,112
<font color="#ffff00">Folks do this crap and a whole
lot worse without battin' an eye.</font>

191
00:31:26,600 --> 00:31:27,919
<font color="#ffff00">After all,</font>

192
00:31:28,600 --> 00:31:31,239
<font color="#ffff00">why slave your life out
when you can just take?</font>

193
00:31:34,880 --> 00:31:38,031
<font color="#ffff00">Are there any real reasons
for livin' right, anyway?</font>

194
00:31:39,920 --> 00:31:43,310
<font color="#ffff00">Mama always thought so, and they
held to her like a moth to light.</font>

195
00:31:44,040 --> 00:31:47,669
<font color="#ffff00">With the hopes of earning
everlasting peace and glory.</font>

196
00:31:48,600 --> 00:31:51,114
<font color="#ffff00">"This life and the next"
she used to say.</font>

197
00:31:53,200 --> 00:31:55,430
<font color="#ffff00">It was all a bloody mean trick.
I don't want none of it.</font>

198
00:32:00,040 --> 00:32:01,712
<font color="#ffff00">Get away from Ricky.</font>

199
00:32:14,200 --> 00:32:16,668
Ruby? Come on back here a sec, would you?

200
00:32:24,120 --> 00:32:26,588
- Welcome back, Mrs. Chambers.
- Well, thank you, Ruby.

201
00:32:27,320 --> 00:32:29,993
- How's everything been?
- Fine. Real nice.

202
00:32:30,840 --> 00:32:32,637
Yeah, the store looks good.

203
00:32:33,880 --> 00:32:35,871
You know, usually I'm afraid
to come back after a trip,

204
00:32:36,040 --> 00:32:37,678
but you did a good job.

205
00:32:38,400 --> 00:32:40,197
I'll ask you to do the
cash drawer, if you don't mind.

206
00:32:52,800 --> 00:32:54,119
Surprise!

207
00:32:54,920 --> 00:32:56,399
How about tonight, we could
meet at the Driftwood?

208
00:32:56,560 --> 00:33:00,348
- I don't think so, Ricky.
- Last time was wonderful.

209
00:33:00,520 --> 00:33:02,954
It was fantastic, I don't
wanna lose that momentum.

210
00:33:03,880 --> 00:33:04,915
It was real nice, Ricky,

211
00:33:05,080 --> 00:33:08,436
- but your Mom's back, and
I just think it's too risky.
- Don't worry about that.

212
00:33:11,560 --> 00:33:14,028
And I didn't come all this way
to be your chippy.

213
00:33:15,360 --> 00:33:18,318
Ricky? Ricky! It's for you.

214
00:33:18,480 --> 00:33:20,072
There in a second, Ma.

215
00:33:22,400 --> 00:33:26,075
I'll give you a few days,
and we'll work it out.

216
00:33:32,080 --> 00:33:35,311
It was fantastic.
Fantastic.

217
